{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"CSS Units","slug":"css-units","subject":"CSS","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"15 mins","prerequisites":["CSS Fonts"],"learning_objectives":["Absolute Units (px, cm, in)","Relative Units (em, rem, %)","Viewport Units (vw, vh, vmin, vmax)","When to use which"],"theory":"CSS has several units for expressing length.\n\n*   **px (Pixels)**: Absolute unit. precise control. Good for borders.\n*   **% (Percentage)**: Relative to the parent element.\n*   **em**: Relative to the font-size of the element (2em = 2 * current font size).\n*   **rem**: Relative to the font-size of the root element (html tag).\n*   **vw/vh**: 1vw = 1% of viewport width. 1vh = 1% of viewport height.","syntax":"h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; }\ndiv { width: 50vw; }","examples":[{"code":"div {\n  height: 100vh;\n  width: 100vw;\n}","output":"A box that covers the entire visible screen.","explanation":"Useful for landing page hero sections."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using px for everything","correction":"Using `rem` for font-size and spacing defaults creates a more accessible design that respects user browser settings.","example":"User sets browser font to 20px -> px sites ignore it. rem sites scale up."}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"Difference between `em` and `rem`?","answer":"`em` is relative to parent/current font size (compounds in nesting). `rem` is relative ONLY to the root (html) font size.","difficulty":"Important"}],"practice_problems":[{"problem":"Set margins to be relative to the root font size.","hint":"Use rem.","solution":"margin: 1rem;","difficulty":"Easy"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Fluid Typography","description":"Using `clamp(1rem, 5vw, 2rem)` for fonts that scale smoothly with viewport size.","code":""}],"exam_notes":["16px is the default browser font size.","1em = 16px (by default)."],"summary":"Mastering relative units is the key to building responsive, accessible websites.","order":3